# Spec 014 — Affordability as a Map Metric

Status: Draft
Owner: <you>
Related: 009-zip-explorer (supersedes its explicit price-to-income-as-metric
deferral), 008-acs-enrichment (the data), 004 (caching this must not break)

## Overview

Price ÷ household income — the classic affordability multiple — has existed
per ZIP since spec 008 but only appears in the detail panel. This spec promotes
it to a fourth map-shading metric ("Afford."), because "where can people like
me actually afford" is the question the whole app exists to answer, and raw
price alone conflates expensive-but-rich areas with genuinely out-of-reach
ones.

## Requirements

- **R1 — Served in the choropleth.** `price_to_income` joins the scalar
  metrics merged into the served GeoJSON (runtime merge from records — no
  data regeneration). The committed-data build mirrors the metric list for
  future full rebuilds.
- **R2 — Cache correctness.** Because the served GeoJSON bytes change while
  the source files do not, the GeoJSON ETag must incorporate a schema
  version (salted hash) so returning browsers do not 304 onto the old shape.
- **R3 — Metric switcher entry.** A fourth metric "Afford." shades by
  price_to_income with per-state equal-count buckets on a distinct
  sequential ramp (darker = higher multiple = less affordable, consistent
  with the darker-is-pricier convention; not reversed), ratio-formatted
  legend ("4.2× – 5.1×"), no-data ZIPs gray, and full URL round-tripping
  (`metric=afford`).

## Non-functional / Constraints

- Purely additive: `urlState`, `MetricSwitcher`, `Legend`, and the
  equal-count machinery all derive from the METRICS config.
- Income data is ACS 5-year (household, pre-tax); the About panel's
  disclaimer covers interpretation limits.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Switching to Afford. reshades the map with visibly distinct ramp and a
      ratio-labeled legend; ZIPs lacking income data render as no-data gray.
- [ ] A browser that had cached the old geojson revalidates and receives the
      new shape (ETag changed via the schema salt).
- [ ] `?metric=afford` deep links round-trip.
- [ ] `pytest` (merge + ETag tests) and `npm run test` (switcher, urlState,
      legend) pass.

## Out of Scope (explicit)

- Affordability modeling beyond the simple multiple (rates, taxes, DTI).
- Reversed/diverging ramp treatments.

## Verification notes

R1/R2 → data_loader tests (property present; salt changes ETag); R3 → UI
tests + visual sweep in a cheap and an expensive state. The human verifies;
the implementing agent does not self-certify done.
